"Andrena afzeliella","212","DD or NE/NA","Steven Falk","","Recently re-added to UK list (it was originally described new to science by Kirby (1802) from Suffolk). Recent scrutiny of ovatula s.l. material suggests it is mostly ovatula s.s. and afzeliella specimens are rare and from the southern part of the ovatula s.l. range.","0",""
"Andrena alfkenella: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena ampla: iso. Falk et al: 2019","212","NT?","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Taxon results from a recent nomenclatural change. There is insufficient data and knowledge to arrive at a supportable conclusion"". This is debatable (as per pur discussion). The data pretty good due to recent scrutiny of proxima s.l. material in NHM and OUM collections plus much correpondence and associated specimen checking (see for e.g. Falk et al., 2019 https://www.researchgate.net/publication/349319333_The_Water-dropwort_mining_bee_Andrena_ampla_Warncke_Hymenoptera_Apidae_new_to_Britain). The two species are strongly allopatric with ampla as a scarce but widespread bee of the coastal SW and coastal Wales (see BWARS map and map in cited paper) with mostly small and fragmented populations associated with Hemlock Water-dropwort stands where suitable nesting habit also exists. Agricultural intensification and coastal development are a threat throughout its range but some sites fall within National Trust areas or SSSIs. The recent split from proxima does not really impact an evaluation. You simply divide the old proxima agg. map into the two species based on the map provided by the paper cited above. This allows a high proportion of the ampla/proxima data to be evaluated to IUCN standards because people have always recorded proxima s.l. and we can be pretty sure which of the two species most records refers to.","1","Disagree"
