"Andrena coitana: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Possibly stable in parts of north and west but a massive decline over large parts of its former range. Much scarcer than the higher profile S41 A. tarsata (with similar habitat requirements) in my expereince.","0","Y"
"Andrena confinis: iso. Wood: 2022","212","NT?","Steven Falk","","Sporadic in occurance but map indicates an ongoing UK decline coupled with a restricted geographic occurrence. Often uses unprotected sites that are vulnerable to development & succession (e.g. sandpits) or development (coastal grasslands).","1","Undergraded?"
"Andrena denticulata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena dorsata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Increasing/expanding","0","Y"
"Andrena falsifica: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT?","Steven Falk","","A scarce, rarely encountered bee with fragmented populations. Heavy reliance on unprotected colliery spoil sites in the Welsh part of its range (Liam Olds will know more). Map indicates substantial UK decline and there is no evidence it is increasing anywhere. Uses Tormentil-rich habitats yet the much more frequent and widespread Tormental-associated Andrena tarsata is given NT status which seems inconsistent. I have also recorded it at Whitbarrow Scar, Cumbria (2012, 2024) but this is not shown on the map (defintely submitted the 2012 record to BWARS). This affects AOO.","1","Undergraded?"
"Andrena ferox: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT?","Steven Falk","","Rare with fragmented populations (see map). Clearly much rarer than the broad habitat it uses (oak-rich woodland). New sites in Kent (recording effort rather than increase?) but seems to have become scarcer in the New Forest (the traditional national hotspot) over recent decades. Apparently cannot now be found at classic locations like Denny Wood (check with George Else) suggesting that climate change or habitat changes may be affecting it here. Map also suggests decline. Narrative cites problems with detecting it (because it gathers pollen from Oak)  but it also forages on Hawthorn and Field Maple, so not convinced this is a major issue as many Andrena species forage from tall trees like tall woodland Wild Cherry, tall woodland Goat Willow etc. Q. Is climate change impacting Oak flowering in southern woods?","1","Undergraded?"
"Andrena flavipes: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Increasing/expanding","0","Y"
"Andrena florea: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Increasing/expanding","0","Y"
"Andrena fucata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
