"Andrena fulvago: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena fuscipes: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena gravida: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","","Steven Falk","","Increasing/expanding","0","Y"
"Andrena haemorrhoa: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena hattorfiana: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Very dependent upon ongoing conservation management through its dependence on scabious-rich unimproved grassland. Despite some evidence of recent increase in counties like Bucks and Oxon, I have also seen protected sites like Wytham Woods have all the scabious-rich grassland haycut in early July meaning the bee (and its Nomad) become locally eliminated that year. Any bee dependent upon scabious flowers is inherently vulnerable to badly-timed cutting or grazing.","0","Y"
"Andrena helvola: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena humilis: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena labialis: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena labiata: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","","Steven Falk","","Increasing/expanding","0","Y"
"Andrena lapponica: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","LC","Steven Falk","","One of the most (often the most) frequent Andrena species of Bilberry-rich habitats in the north and west, with not much evidence of a decline in the north though there is clearly some under-recording of the bee here. I survey the north of England and Scottish Highlands frequently and have needed to target A. lapponica to produce my recent paper on its cuckoo, Nomada glabella (https://www.researchgate.net/publication/361818501_DNA_and_morphological_characterisation_of_the_Bilberry_Mining_Bee_Nomada_glabella_sensu_Stockhert_nec_Thomson_in_Britain_with_discussion_of_the_remaining_variation_within_N_panzeri) so reasonably familiar with it here. Paddy and Liam will have a better idea tha me of how it is faring in the SW and Wales.  Narrative cites ""Climate change at risk of reducing viable habitat area of host plants"" but I think we need a more scientific and informed basis for asserting that climate change will actually reduce Bilberry-rich habitats on the north and west (and I'm not fully convinced because current and projected climate change is not even/linear across the UK especially in the north, plus Bilberry can cope with warmer climates than Scotland in the south). Without such evidence, maybe best stick to LC. But if it does end up as NT, then its cuckoo Nomada glabella will need to graded at least as highly.","1","Overgraded"
"Andrena lathyri","212","CR?","Steven Falk","","No data sheet provided. Last recorded about 1990? Always a Wiltshire rarity but needs a programme of targeted searches because not officially extinct in UK yet so ideally needs including.","0",""
"Andrena marginata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","On the cusp of NT but map suggests less decline than species like A. falsifica or A. confinis, and some scabious-rich grassland tend to have protection through Marsh Fritillary conservation and general unimproved grassland protection etc.","0","Y"
"Andrena minutula: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena minutuloides: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena nigriceps: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Map shows evidence of significant UK decline. Heavy reliance on threatened brownfeld habitat in regions like the Midlands (where badly declined). Scarce and sporadic, increasingly hard to find now. Many of the locations I know for it in the Midlands now developed. ","1","Undergraded?"
"Andrena nigroaenea: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena nigrospina: iso. Else & Edwards: 2018","212","VU","Steven Falk","","No narrative provided but recent formal split from A. pilipes likely to be the reason for DD. However, there has been a lot of scrutity of nigrospina recently (Jukes, Falk, RSPB Sandy, Norfolk bee recorders etc.) and this creates a data imperfect but not data deficient situation. It is also relatively easy to separate nigrospina data from pilipes data based on different ranges, flight periods, habitat preferences & their different cuckoo Nomads (N. fulvicornis on pilipes, N. subcornuta on nigrospina). This accumulated data shows nigrospina is a rare, vulnerable species with few, highly fragmented populations (as per map which I think portrays the modern status fairly well except for a lack of several south Essex records), a high proportion of which are based on unprotected arable land on very sandy ground with abundant Wild Radish (an increasingly less common sight on farmland) or crucifer-rich, sandy brownfield land (an unusual & widely threatened category of brownfield found esp in Thames Gateway and Kent). Some of its few sites are known to be subject to development proposals (e.g. sites in Essex & Norfolk). Longer term evidence from museums of a big national decline with loss from counties such as Warwickshire. Also significant recent decline in its former national hotspot in Staffs/Worcs (cannot be found at Highgate Common now and Blackstone Farm site has been converted largely from flowery arable with strong nigrospina/subcornuta populations to permanent grassland with a tiny remnant population (Falk 2022 report to Worcs WT, Andy Jukes work etc.). In summary, data is not really deficient - we  have accumulated a pretty good understanding of the species and its circumstances on the ground.","1","Disagree"
"Andrena nitida: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena nitidiuscula: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Like A. marginata, on cusp of NT","0","Y"
"Andrena niveata: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","NT or VU","Steven Falk","","I've had far too many recent encounters with A. niveata in Kent and Sussex to justify EN status (I think I'm responsible for a high proportion of the modern data for this species due to targeted surveys). As inferred in the narrative The South Downs population largely uses crucifer-rich arable margins (foraging on Hedge Mustard and Charlock), a frequent habitat on the East Sussex South Downs but one poorly recorded by Hymenopterists. The narrative states ""Intensification of agriculture is perceived as a moderate probability/high threat risk. This particularly covers conversion to permanent pasture, vineyards, and cereal crops""  but I visit the East Sussex South Downs regularly and cannot see any major changes from when I recorded it widely there a couple of decades ago. Certainly no sign of any vineyards! There is also a strong/extensive population in the Sandwich Bay area (good numbers in both 2019 and 2023) using crucifer-rich suburban brownfield land and golf links - foraging on Hoary Mustard, Hedge Mustard and Charlock in areas of disturbed weedy ground which occurs widely in the area. I suspect if more crucifer-rich brownfield sites in Kent were systematically surveyed, this bee would prove to be quite widespread, but it needs targeted recording as I did in the South Downs. The dataset for this bee is demonstrably skewed significantly just by my single targeted efforts in Sussex and Kent meaning it is not a stable basis for establishing a threat status without expert opinion adjustment. On balance, NT or VU seem more appropriate than EN, especially given that it is not just confined to arable margins and is probably under-recorded.","1","Overgraded"
"Andrena ovatula","212","LC","Steven Falk","","No data sheet provided. I'm guessing that the recent discovery of A. afzeliella in the UK (hiding under ovatula) is the reason for the exclusion of ovatula. But I've checked lots of ovatula material now, and I know that Ivan Wright has checked OUM, and this all suggests that the vast majority of ovatula s.l. records are ovatula s.s. with afzeliella seemingly only a tiny proportion and only from the very south of ovatula's UK range. So I would regard this as a data imperfect but not a data deficient situation. It supports a LC status for ovatula s.s. and a DD/NE/NA status for afzeliella. As a general observation, I'm uncomfortable with the discovery of a new species so readily knocking out inclusion of a well-know, checklisted species. It's the equivalent of leaving Chiffchaff off an IUCN review because Siberian and Caucasion Chiffchaffs have been recorded in the UK as vagrants. Why not simply evlauate ovatula s.l. with the caveat that it might contain a small proprtion of afziliella records. That seems less controversial than giving DD to such as well-known species.","0",""
"Andrena pilipes: iso. Else & Edwards: 2018","212","LC","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Taxon results from a recent nomenclatural change. There is insufficient data and knowledge to arrive at a supportable conclusion"" (and this is presumably why nigrospina is given DD too) but there s relativly little overlap of the populations, a different flight period, habitat preference & Nomada cuckoo to A. nigrospina,  allowing separation of much pilipes data. That data shows pilipes is a widespread, coastal-biased species that is frequent in areas like the SW England and Thames Estuary. Maybe some decline in the east, but locally common in the west. Status not that different to A. thoracica (LC) alonside whihc it usually occurs, and often in larger numbers, but somewhat less widespread. Data imperfect not data deficient?","1","Disagree"
"Andrena polita: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","CR","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Recent re-colonist. There is not enough data to come to any supportable conclusion"". But could be legitinmately argued that the recent Kent records represent relict Kent populations rather than recolonisation of UK, given they are close to the old Kent records. That would make it one of Britain's rarest and most threatened bees, on par with Osmia xanthomelana. I'd suggest using precautionaly principle as support for CR, given we cannot prove one hypothesis over the other.","1","Disagree"
"Andrena praecox: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena proxima: iso. Falk et al: 2019","212","LC","Steven Falk","","See ampla notes. Relatively easy to separate proxima s.s. records from ampla (they are largely allopatric) and the pair have been subject of much recent verification of museum/private material since ampla was discovered in UK. Shows proxima s.s. is a widespread but localised bee that is increasing in areas such as East Anglia. Data imperfect but not deficient.","1","Disagree"
"Andrena rosae: iso. Else & Edwards: 2018","212","NT","Steven Falk","","No data sheet/narrative provided. Rare with highly fragmented populations (see map), now largely confined to SW England and Pembrokeshire where very local and vulnerable to agricultural intensification and coastal development (as per A. simillima). Evidence for long-term UK decline historically, little evidence for any increase anywhere (the recent Oxon record may be a vagrant as I regularly target spring mining bees here). But so rare that targeted effort by 1-2 recorders (e.g Paddy Saunders, John Walters in SW, Liam Olds in Wales) could give a false impression of increase. That is always the risk with these very rare bees. Needs to be flagged that this bivoltine species makes a big demand on the landscape because the two generations forage in very different habitats (spring generation targets Blackthorn scrub or willow-rich areas whilst summer generation is heavily dependent upon abundant Angelica in wet, unimproved grassland, plus it also needs nesting and lekking habitats in warm and sheltered stretches of coastline. In other words, it needs a specific and unusual type of coastal habitat mosaic, and if either the spring or summer foraging habitats are lost, the entire population goes because it cannot survive as just a spring generation or just a summer generation.","1","Undergraded?"
"Andrena ruficrus: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Widespread and cleary under-recorded in north (I've had quite a few encountes in the Scottsh Highlands recently, which is full of Salix-rich habitat)","0","Y"
"Andrena scotica","212","LC","Steven Falk","","No data sheet - quite a surprise given it is such an easily-identified, common and well known bee that is well characterised in Falk (2015) and Else & Edwards (2018) and fully accepted in the UKSI. I'm assuming this exclusion is because of taxonomic confusion surrounding the scotica/trimmerana complex on the continent, which has resulted in Mike aggregating data for the species in a manner that makes it hard to disaggregate. Thats's truly infortunate and is the the equivalent of leaving Herring Gull and Lesser BB Gull off a UK status review because ornithologists can't decide how to split up the Herring/Yellow-legged/Caspian/Steppe Gull complex. I'm aso wondering if historic misapplication of the name trimmerana (due to older Perkins keys) has resulted in Mike aggregratinf data for teh two taxa, but they were clearly treated as two species when I prepared the 1991 NCC review. In other words, I have no idea why there was a need not to treat them as two different taxa. Whatever the reason, scotica is clearly LC and not showing any sign of serious decline that I can detect. Note: Really important to cover all the species in the UKSI and not to attempt to use this status review to reshape the official British checklist.","0",""
"Andrena russala: iso. Praz et al: 2022","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena semilaevis: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena simillima: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT or VU","Steven Falk","","Very rare with highly fragmented populations (see map), often at unprotected sites with risk of development or agricultural intensification (e.g. North Cornwall coast). Some evidence of long-term UK decline (though it has always been very rare). Data sheet shows relatively large number of recent records which I suspect are largely from Paddy Saunders monitoring at its Cornish sites but there is no indication of the number of sites involved or whether it is increasing on the ground.  No evidence of an increase anywhere, though recent (2024?) rediscovery in Kent was encouraging (but clearly critically rare here). Like A. niveata, a rare species where targeted activity by just 1-2 people could create the impression of increase when it is actually vulnerable and decreasing on the ground. Paddy Saunders has taken me to some of its N. Cornwall sites. Often small, isolated areas of rough, flowery grassland surrounded by intensive farmland, along a coastline with a fair amount of development/tourism pressure. Also need to flag that it needs abundant Common Knapweed plus Bramble for foraging. These are not universally abundant along the N. Cornwall coast, and that is probably why the bee is so localised (and vulnerable) here.","1","Strongly disagree"
"Andrena subopaca: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena synadelpha: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena tarsata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","LC?","Steven Falk","","Much evidence of a decline in south and east of Britain but not that rare in west and north where it is probably under-recorded even in view of some targeted work due to its S41 status and Buglife's concern with it. Tormentil-rich habitat is widespread and relatively unthreatened in the north and west. Narrative states ""potential loser to climate change due to warming climate"" but I think we need to be cautious here for reasons explained under A. lapponica. Needs to be stated that it is much easier to find A. tarsata than Andrena coitana or A. falsifica which have similar habitat preferences. Paddy Saunders has good tarsata data from the SW. If it stays at NT I think you also need to use that grade for A. falsifica.","1","Overgraded?"
"Andrena thoracica: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena tibialis: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Andrena trimmerana","212","LC","Steven Falk","","See notes for A. scotica. There is very little confusion regarding the taxonomic identity and status of this bee in UK and ih been treated as a good spcies for at least 30 yrs. It is clearly not the same as A. scotica (different morphologically and ecologically even if mtCO1 does not segregate them - mtCO1 does not segregate several UK bee spp) and is treated as a good species in all the key British literature plus the UKSI. Wdespread but local in most areass with noticeable expansion/increase within the Midlands over tha past decade. Really unfortunate that it has ended up as DD. Can BWARS trimmerana/scotica data be disaggregated?","0",""
