"Arachnospila consobrina: iso. Day: 1988","212","NT or VU","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""The majority of the known population exists in one small area which is vulnerable to a single storm surge"". It is indeed rare and restricted now (basically dunes of S. Wales and north Norfolk) but not quite as rare and vulnerable as suggested here and the NBN data (seemingly from bona fide sources) paints a less alarming picture with recent records from several large/resilient dune systems and not a single vulnerable site. I recorded it at Scolt Head Island in 2024 which shows it still persists in Norfolk (the map suggests it may have gone from this area). NT or VU seems best fit, similar to the situation with Coelioxys mandibularis (which has a very similar distribution and status).","1","Overgraded?"
