"Auplopus carbonarius: iso. Day: 1988","212","","Steven Falk","","Increasing/expanding","0","Y"
"Bombus barbutellus: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Bombus bohemicus: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","NT","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Retreating north, but potential confusion in identification with B. vestalis: iso. Cameron et al: 2007 which is expanding into the north. This is suspected to have inflated the record numbers from the 10 year period, hiding a longer-term decline"" and also suggests decline of its hosts. Much evidence for a decline in lowland southern/central England (where it was always much less common than in the north) and for misidentication issues with B. vestalis but I do lots of recording in Scotland and upland northern England and still find it to be frequent in the Scottish Highlands, Yorkshire Dales and North Pennines, where its hosts are abundant and the climate is cooler. Has Richard Comont (BBCT) been consulted? I think NT is the most appropriate grade without more hard evidence of a decline in the north.","1","Overgraded?"
"Bombus campestris: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","LC?","Steven Falk","","Some evidence of a decline but less so according to map than B. barbutellus (which is afforded LC status). One of those bees that shows fluctuations in my experience. Worth checking with Richard Comont (BBCT).  You need to separate fluctuations from long-term trends but 10 year appraisal periods don't make this easy.","1","Overgraded?"
"Bombus cryptarum: iso. Murray et al: 2008","212","LC","Steven Falk","","My sequenced male material suggests this is the commonest white-tail of upland areas such as the Pennines. Yorkshire Dales, and parts of the Scottish Highlands, especially sheep fells and on exposed Magnesium Limestone areas where heathers are less abundant but clovers and BFT are frequent. ","1","Disagree"
"Bombus distinguendus: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Bombus hortorum: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Bombus humilis: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Bombus hypnorum: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Bombus jonellus: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Bombus lapidarius: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Bombus lucorum agg: iso. Murray et al: 2008","212","","Steven Falk","","We know enough about the distribution of B. cryptarum, B. lucorum and B. magnus to avouid using this aggregate taxon. But if aggregate taxa are alloweed, why no use them for Andrena ovatula s.l., Nomada panzeri s.l. etc.","1","Superfluous taxon?"
"Bombus lucorum: iso. Murray et al: 2008","212","LC","Steven Falk","","Lucorum s.s. males are readily distinguished by colour pattern from magnus and cryptarum without the need for DNA analysisand show it is widespread in UK and locally frequent though possibly declined in southern England.  The range overlaps with magnus and cryptarum (all three coexist in some upland areas with lusher valley systems) but it seems to be the maon/exclusive white-tail of agricultural and urban areas of  lowland south and east England.","1","Disagree"
"Bombus magnus: iso. Murray et al: 2008","212","LC","Steven Falk","","Queens (many of which are readily distinguished from cryptarum and lucorum s.s.) and males (with DNA support) show this is a widespread and locally common species in heather-rich habitats of north and west Britain, esp Western Isles, Cairngorms, SW England, Yorkshire Dales and N. Pennines. Was also present in the New Forest about 20 yrs ago (I've not checked since). Imperfect data but perhaps enough to avoid DD. ","1","Disagree"
"Bombus monticola: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","LC?","Steven Falk","","No data sheet provided. As per B. bohemicus, evidence of a decline in southern England (where it was never common) and maybe South Wales - but much less of a decline in southern England than bohemicus. Still widespread and common in northern England and the Scottish Highlands where suitable habitat is widespread and relatively unthreatened. Mike has made a case for excessive sheep-grazing of the uplands to be an issue but it is not that B&W because some sheep-grazing can promote the clovers and BFT it rerquires in addition to heathers, Bilberry and willows. I still see it in good numbers on my wide-ranging travels in the north. The climate change argument is as per Andrena lapponica. Worth discussing with Richard Comont.","1","Overgraded?"
"Bombus muscorum: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","NT?","Steven Falk","","No data sheet provided. There has been a big historic decline (esp inland) that may be continuing in some areas such as the south and east coasts of England (esp East Anglia, Lincolnshire and Thames Estuary area). A bumblebee that seems to be vulnerable to climate change esp warming of south. Historically was present well inland (flagged because it was a decline like we've seen with bohemicus but many decades earlier). Also prone to misidentification with B. humilis. Worth discussing with Richard Comont.","1","Undergraded?"
"Bombus pascuorum: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
