"Bombus rupestris: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","Increasing/expanding.","0","Y"
"Bombus soroeensis: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","NT","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Targeted survey effort has entirely distorted the model (not sure I understand this - surely targeted surveying is a good thing)"" and ""Significant confusion with Bombus terrestris"". Not sure I agree with either. There has been enough survey work and verification to provide a pretty accurate picture of where it occurs today and where it has been historically lost. It is clearly very scarce and badly declined in England and Wales (more so than map shows because it lacks a lot of museum and literature records) and there no evidence of increase anywhere. Datasheet seems to show a significant tailing off of records recently. More stable in the Scottish Highlands and North Pennines (but still very localised requiring flowers like Wild raspberry for queen foraging and DB Scabious for late summer foraging). The inconsistency with Bombus bohemicus and B.monticola statuses is flagged, as both of these bumblebees that have always been more frequent and widespread than soroeensis, seem to show no greater decline, yet receive IUCN statuses. Strongly recommend that B. soroeensis ends up with no lower a status than either bohemicus or monticola.","1","Disagree"
