"Coelioxys mandibularis: iso. Amiet et al: 2004","212","NT or VU","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""The majority of the population exists in a narrow strip of dune, which is at risk of damage during storm events"". That is inccurate as it still occurs at several large and broad dune systems (including Sandwich Bay, Kenfig, Merthyr Mawr, Oxwich, Stackpole, Whiteford - Liam will know all the current Welsh locations) where it is  relatively safe from storm damage. I still find it quite readily on dunes of Sandwich Bay and South Wales (where hosts are common), and Liam Olds tells me he finds it readily at Welsh dunes. It's a bit reminscent of the Andrena niveata situation. Map does not support EN either and both Megachile hosts remain common in its core areas.","1","Overgraded"
"Coelioxys quadridentata: iso. Amiet et al: 2004","212","CR","Steven Falk","","Narrative invokes ""insufficient data"". Not sure why DD is used. Leafcutter bees are relatively well-recorded and readily identifiable. All the evidence for quadridentata points to a catastrophic collapse of the UK population (as also seen in Anthophora retusa). The map (so presumably the BWARS dataset) does not include older records from museum collections and literature which reveal that it was once more widespread though never common. ","1","Disagree"
