"Colletes halophilus: iso. Guichard: 1974","212","LC ","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""All sites live at sea level, with minimal ability to rapidly adapt. Magnitude of impact will depend on the sea level mitigation measures, particularly in managed retreats of sea wall defences"". I've probably seen more halophilus locations than anybody else in the UK as a result of big coastal surveys in S and E England and ongoing EA contract work. It is actually surprisingly adaptable (even occurs within the industrialised Immingham Port and suburban Humberside). Known to be much more frequent and widespread along the east coast than previously thought (e.g. semi-continuous presence along Lincolnshire and North Norfolk coast) and clear evidence of recent colonisation of the west coast (Somerset, Lancs, Cumbria) plus a big recent jump north to Hartlepool (in many ways behaving/spreading like a coastal Ivy Bee). Not convinced it is anywhere near as threatened as Buglife etc. have suggested, and the BWARS map is missing some important recent data. Rising sea level is generally used to support S41 listing and European IUCN status but saltmarsh is actually accreting along some parts of the east coast plus the RSPB are doing a good job of maintaining/creating brackish coastal areas. Also worth noting that Sea Aster can occur in a variety of brackish habitats, and quickly colonises man-made lagoons, and tidal channels. The bee will nest in sea banks, upper saltmarsh hillocks (e.g. Colne Point), stabilised coastal dunes (e.g. Donna Nook), and sometimes man-made surfaces of brownfield sites and landscaped areas (several sites in Essex) i.e. it is adaptable like the closely-related Ivy Bee. We need to give this species further thought because the increasing trend does not support NT.","1","Overgraded?"
