"Dolichovespula norwegica: iso. Archer: 1989","212","LC?","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Targeted survey effort in NE Scotland distort figures. Observed declines in abundance during survey work, particularly in southern England, but also stretching to Lancashire"". Not sure that targeted effort in the south does anything more than even out the more intensive aculeate recording you get in the south and get us closer to to truth (a good thing). I agree that it  has declined in south and east but much less so than species such as Bombus bohemicus or Vespula rufa, as I still see it in Warks and Oxon. It is still frequent and seemingly unthreatened in north (see map). Important not to exaggerate decline in the north of its range or to overplay the climate change card (which is full of uncertainties). Much less declined than Vespula rufa (a useful contrast).","1","Overgraded?"
"Dolichovespula saxonica: iso. Archer: 1989","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Dolichovespula sylvestris: iso. Archer: 1989","212","LC?","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Data in the second time slice (2017-2021) is heavily biased by the addition of a number of records from north-east Scotland. In the same period, the area south of the Severn-Wash line has experienced a major loss in both number of records and number of tetrads. Given that this southern area has the greatest number and frequency of surveys, the absence is likely to be true"". I also think it has declined in the south and east but it seems to remain frequent in many parts of UK, especially in north and west (see map). Remember that social wasps can take several years to recover from one bad year and populations fluctuate a lot at the moment due to cold springs, wet summers or drought summers, so this could account for 2017-2021 dip. Also perplexed by how recording effort by one individual is flagged as an issue here (for a fairly frequent species wher the skewing impact will be lower) but not for rarities like Andrena simillima or A. niveata where this has a much greater skewing impact.","1","Overgraded?"
"Dryudella pinguis: iso. Bitsch et al: 2001","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
