"Euodynerus quadrifasciatus: iso. Early: 2018","212","VU","Steven Falk","","Narrative flags insuffient data but that is because it is very rare and does not seem to be a justification for DD. Known from just a few coastal shingle sites (where vulnerable to storm damage and coastal development), and very occasionally gravelly sites inland (some of which are brownfield). See map (though this lacks its Prawle Point Devon site discovered by John Walters a few years ago). Highly fragmented populations, no evidence of an increase anywhere. Very hard to find despite being a fairly conspicuous wasp. Unclear why species such as Coelioxys mandibularis and Arachnospila consobrina are treated differently. Rarer than the shingle-associated Hylaeus annularis.","1","Disagree"
