"Halictus eurygnathus: iso. Amiet et al: 2001","212","NT or VU","Steven Falk","","Incredibly restricted (maybe 10 known sites?), using only a tiny fraction of apparently suitable habitat in the South Downs (see map). When a species is this rare, it has to be especially vulnerable to climatic extremes (espcially extreme summer droughts), though most of its sites are well managed for chalk grassland and protected. Forages on a variety of flowers but abundant Greater Knapweed seems to be an obligate requirement (in the same way as Ivy is required by the oligolectic Ivy Bee) and this plant is not a universal feature of chalk grassland on the South Downs.","1","Undergraded?"
