"Hylaeus annularis: iso. Notton and Dathe: 2008","212","NT or VU","Steven Falk","","No data sheet provided and no obvious justification for DD. Presumably this is due to past nomenclatural confusion with H. dilatatus but if so, that's invalid because there has been plenty of time to assess records of the two and it is now clear that H. annularis is a rare and restricted coastal shingle specialist of southern England where it is vulnerable to storm damage, coastal development and coastal engineering. We now have a pretty good idea of its distribution and precise locations i.e. it is not significantly under-recorded. No evidence of increase but some examples of shingle areas within its core range being damaged/destroyed/developed in recent years (especially in Sussex, Kent). NT or VU fit best. Worth highlighting contrast with Coelioxys mandibularis as I think they have a lot in common and need a similar status.","1","Disagree"
