"Nomada argentata: iso. Amiet et al: 2007","212","NT?","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Very low detectability, even with focused survey effort"". I disagree. You find it on the same scabious flowers that the host uses, but the simple fact is that it is much scarcer and more restricted than the host (as is often the case with nomad bees). Occurs as small, fragmented populations now, with some evidence of decline evident in the map and literature (e.g Powers, 2024). Ongoing loss and deterioration of scabious-rich habitats seems to be a widespread issue (e.g. Red Lodge, Suffolk and some Breckland sites) and I'm pretty sure local development pressure is an issue in some areas (Marsh Fritillary data could be useful as this nomad is most frequent at DBS-rich sites). Remember that it only takes one year of heavy late summer grazing of a scabious-rich site to eradicate the host and nomad even if the plant survives. When I think of the statuses afforded to bees like Bombus bohemicus it is very strange to see bees like this and A. simillima end up with LC.","1","Undergraded?"
"Nomada armata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT?","Steven Falk","","Small, fragmented populations vulnerable to loss of scabious-rich grassland, development pressure in counties like Oxon, plus badly timed cutting or grazing (remember that just one year of late-summer grazing or July haycutting can eradiacate this bee and its host). Strong evidence of decline in some areas (e.g. SW) but some indications of stabilty and increase in counties like Oxon and Bucls. But in 2024, the scabious-rich areas of Wytham Woods where this bee and its host were recently recorded were haycut in early July, so no scabious flowers and no sign (likely elmination) of the bees. ","1","Undergraded?"
"Nomada baccata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Nomada bifasciata: iso. Amiet et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","Recent colonist","0","Y"
"Nomada conjungens: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","On the cusp I reckon. Much scarcer than the two hosts. Very few recent records though indication of a recent expansion in East Anglia where A. proxima seems to be increasing.","1","Undergraded?"
"Nomada errans","212","CR?","Steven Falk","","Last recorded from near Swanage in 1982. Not officially Extinct and could be hanging on somewhere along the Dorset coast (esp MOD areas that are hard to access). The host bee (Andrena nitidiuscula) is not that rare in Daucus-rich grassland along the south coast. ","0",""
"Nomada fabriciana: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Nomada facilis: iso. Notton & Norman: 2017","212","NT?","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Nomenclatural split with no time to obtain data yet"". Not really true. David Notton checked collections of NHM and OUM, many recorders checked their private collections, and some new records have come to light since it was split from N. integra. I think that we have a pretty good idea of the range and status of facilis in the UK now, especially given that we know roughly where its host lives (A. humilis/N. facilis are more calcicolous and much scarcer and southern-biased than A. humilis/N. integra s.s.). Widespread but extremely localised in southern England. Data imperfect but not really deficient.","1","Disagree"
"Nomada ferruginata: iso. Amiet et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
