"Nomada fulvicornis: iso. Falk: 2004","212","LC","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Nomenclatural split with further potential taxa contained"". It was indeed affected by the splitting off of N. subcornuta but there has been lots of checking of museum collections (notably NHM, OUM), private collections etc. and correspondence which shows that the vast majority of fulvicornis s.l. records relate to fulvicornis s.s. as opposed to subcornuta, and we now have a pretty good idea which of the fulvicornis s.l. records relate to subcornuta (though the two have been recorded alongside each other at places like Highgate). See https://www.researchgate.net/publication/359402460_The_story_behind_Kirby's_Nomad_bee_Nomada_subcornuta_Kirby_1802) for background. In other words, if you remove the known subcornuta records from the BWARS fulvicornis map, you can assess fulvicornis s.s. However, It is now clear that fulvicornis s.s. is widespread, LC, and not showing a strong decline. Data imperfect not data deficient!","1","Disagree"
"Nomada 'glabella' iso. Falk et al. 2022","212","LC","Steven Falk","","Added to the British list by Falk et al. 2022 (https://www.researchgate.net/publication/361818501_DNA_and_morphological_characterisation_of_the_Bilberry_Mining_Bee_Nomada_glabella_sensu_Stockhert_nec_Thomson_in_Britain_with_discussion_of_the_remaining_variation_within_N_panzeri). which involved checking collections of NHM, OUM, much correspondence and survey work. Widespread in Bilberry-rich habitats of the north and west plus some heathland sites in Midlands and one Sussex site (see map in publications) where it occurs at a fairly high proportion of host sites (host is Bilberry-associated Andrena lapponica). Probably the commonest nomad bee in the Cairngorms but also frequent in some other areas. Data impefect but not deficient, indicating LC, or NT if you want to play the climate change card (but grading must account for any grade given to its host).","0",""
"Nomada goodeniana: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Nomada guttulata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Increasing/expanding","0","Y"
"Nomada hirtipes: iso. Amiet et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Nomada integra: iso. Notton & Norman: 2017","212","LC or NT?","Steven Falk","","DD based on nomenclatural split but see my notes for N. facilis. Most of the checked integra s.l. material proves to be integra s.s. with very little relating to facilis. On this basis I think we can confidently say integra s.s. is widespread. Some evidence of a UK decline in the map. If you remove known facilis records from the BWARS integra s.l. map, you can assess N. integra s.s. Data imperfect not data deficient.","1","Disagree"
"Nomada lathburiana: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","Increasing/expanding","0","Y"
"Nomada leucophthalma: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Nomada marshamella: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Nomada panzeri","212","LC","Steven Falk","","Another example of a common species has been omitted from this assessment following a taxonomic split. If you remove known glabella data from the BWARS dataset, the vast majority of the panzeri s.l. data (especially from areas lacking Bilberry) will be panzeri s.s. allowing assessment. My records and the other panzeri s.l. material I've checked shows that panzeri s.s. is widespread and frequent with little sign of an obvious decline - clearly LC. ","0",""
"Nomada obtusifrons: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Scarcity of data prevents assessment "" but surely that is simply penalising a species for being scarce and does not treally justify DD. It is a readily identified species that is clearly scarce and localised in the north and west, mostly attacking Andrena coitana (NT) and less often A, tarsata (NT). Has declined in south and east like its hosts but I suspect it is under-recorded in Wales and Scotland. I found it at two Perthshire sites in 2024 which is an area shown blank on the BWARS map. NT seems to fit best.","1","Disagree"
"Nomada roberjeotiana: iso. Amiet et al: 2007","212","NT or VU","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Localised and very under-recorded. No threats known, but efforts hampered by low detection of taxon"". Q how do you know it is under-recorded? The S41 host (the Tormentil-associated Andrena tarsata) has been relatively well recorded which ought ot have flushed out records of roberjeotiana if it was present. You also state that no threats are known, yet it relies on a S41 host that is known to have declined and that you state might be impacted by climate change. N. roberjeotiana is a distinctive, easily recognised bee that is clearly very rare and much scarcer than the host. The circumstances are very similar to N. obtusifrons and I'd argue that they both deserve NT. Also, roberjeoataina must nt be graded lower than its host, Andrena tarsata. Paddy Saunders has good data from the SW.","1","Disagree"
"Nomada ruficornis: iso. Amiet et al: 2007","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
