"Nomada subcornuta iso. Falk, 2015","212","VU","Steven Falk","","No data sheet provided. See my notes for N. fulvicornis and the host bee Andrena nigrospina. Added to the British 9 years ago by Falk (2015) so not that recently, and we have a pretty good idea of where N. subcornuta occurs today, the threats on the ground, and its historic distribution (by checking collections of NHM, OUM and correspondence - see https://www.researchgate.net/publication/359402460_The_story_behind_Kirby's_Nomad_bee_Nomada_subcornuta_Kirby_1802. Clearly very rare, and vulnerable to the loss of suitable arable margins (with abundant Wild Radish and very sandy ground) and the crucifer-rich, sandy brownfield sites required by the host. Serious decline in the W. Midlands part of its range (see nigrospina notes). and strong evidence of a decline of the host throughout its UK range with a high level of threat to the few brownfield sites it still survives at.","0",""
