"Osmia uncinata: iso. Else & Edwards: 1996","212","NT or VU?","Steven Falk","","No data sheet provided. Not really common anywhere within its range and seemingly missing from many old pinewoods (probably because it needs plenfiful Bird's-foot Trefoil which is far from a typical plant of pinewoods!). Evidence of a decline in Cairngorms/Strathspey (it's historic hotspot) due to loss of BFT. Stewart Taylor ex RSPB warden Abernethy shared all his Abernethy data with me in 2022 showing that it is now restricted to just a few areas where there good patches of BFT (BFT is pretty rare in Abernethy Forest). I've surveyed many of the classic Cairngorms pinewoods in recent years in late May/early June but have only seen it once (see: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/370100523_An_entomological_survey_of_some_Cairngorms_sites_2022). I think it is potentially VU and it is nonsensical that it should end up at LC when it is so much rarer and vulnerable than bees such as Bombus bohemicus, B. lapponica, Andrena lapponica that it coexists with. It's like grading Little Tern as LC whilst you grade the Herring Gulls flying alongside it as NT. It is also vulnerable to summer forest fires (an increasing threat in the Cairngorms which contains some of the most combustable landscapes in the UK), the affects of early summer heatwaves (increasingly frequent in the Highlands), and forestry operations (which can eliminate BFT along rides). ","1","Undergraded"
