"Pemphredon fabricii","212","VU","Steven Falk","","Added to British list by Falk & Early, 2021 (https://www.researchgate.net/publication/349590544_Pemphredon_fabricii_Hymenoptera_Crabronidae_new_to_Britain). Current evidence suggests a rare species confined to stressed valley mire reedbeds (with Lipara 'cigar galls') in the New Forest. Very restricted and could be vulnerable to climate change. On the Continent it seems to avoid dense, lush reedbeds, so it seems to have very special needs that only lowland valley mire in the New Forest (a very restricted habitat) may meet.","0",""
"Pemphredon inornata: iso. Dollfuss: 1995","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Pemphredon lugubris: iso. Dollfuss: 1995","212","","Steven Falk","","","0","Y"
"Pemphredon morio: iso. Dollfuss: 1995","212","LC?","Steven Falk","","Narrative states ""Considered to be multiple species based on genetic information. No non-genetic identification methods found or published. Status of the particular species composition in the project area is unknown and requires more information"". Under these circumstances (and until something concrete is published), would it not make more sense to assess it as iso Falk & Early, 2021 (i.e. morio s.l)? Again, I'm uncomfortable by the extent to which taxonomic uncertainties have impacted this review when it ought to be sticking to the official UKSI checklists unless there is a strong over-riding reason.","1","Disagree"
"Pemphredon rugifer: iso. Dollfuss: 1995","212","LC?","Steven Falk","","No data sheet provided. As per previous species, assess rugifer s.l. (sensu Falk & Early, 2021) and forget about the ongoing arguments about whether it is one species or two at the moment.","1","Disagree"
