"Symmorphus connexus: iso. Richards: 1980","212","NT?","Steven Falk","","Insufficient data invoked as reason for DD. Surprised by this as it is a well-defined, long-recognised, readily-identified species, in a well-recorded part of southern England, with fairly well understood ecology. Clearly a scarce species of Aspen-rich woods with evidence of decline in the map. Vulnerable to Aspen clearance (Aspen often regarded as a 'weed tree' by foresters) and possibly to the impact of climate change on its prey. Lack of records through rarity cannot be a justification for DD alone.","1","Disagree"
"Symmorphus crassicornis: iso. Richards: 1980","212","","Steven Falk","","on the cusp of NT I reckon. A species of Aspen woods (as per previous species) plus dune slacks with Creeping Willow (the prey leaf beetle, Chrysomela populi occurs in two different habitats). But the wasp uncommon in both habitat categories and is much scarcer the the prey species..","0","Y"
