"Andrena alfkenella: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Evidence of Decline SW. Needs further checking by BWARS /experts or species for watch list. ","0","Y"
"Andrena ampla: iso. Falk et al: 2019","212","NT / LC","Paddy Saunders","","Sites with A. ampla and or  A.promixa s.l. in SW very scarce, THREATS climate risks increased extreme weather events causing stochastic risks of localized extinctions as sites strongly associated with soft cliff slippages. Threats - long term trend of scrub succession on south Cornwall /Devon and development risks.","1","disagree"
"Andrena coitana: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Decline in Devon and Cornwall. Only 2 modern sites in Cornwall only a few sites in Devon. Former distribution much wider. Habitat and ecology in UK needs more research. THREATS associated with upland habitats climate risk - REF Saunders 23","0","Y"
"Andrena falsifica: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT ?","Paddy Saunders","","Evidence of decline in SW. Threats ? Climate risk is a upland species ?","1","disagree /check"
"Andrena fucata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Agree. Fairly common bee, but may need double checking for future climate risk as usually more upland species ","0","Y"
"Andrena hattorfiana: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","???","Paddy Saunders","","Increased recording effort likely to have masked trends. In Cornwall host population is still fragmented with the populations in Cornwall restricted to very small dune edge areas.  The only Devon site is very small with a tiny availability of flower resources. Threats-unimproved grassland habitats still have habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices as a highly specialized species this threat is more critical for a highly specialist species. Although the bee can survive on isolated sites the ability to ""move northwards"" is very questionable as species rich calcerous grassland are not universal and necessarily connected. High Conservation dependence on specialised sites (both protected sites and subsidies) and cessation of conservation programme likely to result in higher threat level in short term. (In Cornwall) Threat -coastal development.","0","Y"
"Andrena lapponica: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Populations in Cornwall very small and isolated. Larger populations in Devon, but most upland and high altitude","0","Y"
"Andrena marginata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT ","Paddy Saunders","","Likely to be extinct Devon and Cornwall. (All the Devon and Cornwall sites have been rechecked recently which may reduce the EOO AOO). Possibly declining Somerset and difficult to find in Dorset. Evidence of UK decline in food plant https://plantatlas2020.org/atlas/2cd4p9h.23w. Threats-unimproved grassland habitats still have habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices as a highly specialized species this threat is more critical. High Conservation dependence on specialised sites (both protected sites and subsidies) and cessation of conservation programme likely to result in higher threat level in short term.    B2 = VU ??   ","1","disagree"
"Andrena nitidiuscula: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","???","Paddy Saunders","","Some evidence of decline in SW. Needs more checking by BWARS. On the South Coast of the SW scrub succession is a particular threat to potential habitat of this bee. Conservation dependence as usually associated with specialized unimproved grassland and cessation of conservation programme likely to result in higher threat level in short term.","1","check"
"Andrena proxima: iso. Falk et al: 2019","212","LC ","Paddy Saunders","","Disagree DD is right category, ","1","disagree"
"Andrena rosae: iso. Else & Edwards: 2018","212","NT ","Paddy Saunders","","AOO/EOO may underestimate distribution as high proportion of grid squares sea. Andrena rosae populations outside the strong population in West Penwith are very small and fragmented with evidence of decline. e.g. Bodmin moor only one site, very small numbers present on Lizard and maybe declining on the north coast of Cornwall. Exmoor and Dartmoor high historical decline and may be extinct. http://kernowecology.co.uk/Publications/BWARSNewsletterAutumn2020AndrenarosaePatrickSaunders.pdf Threats climate risk the species distribution in Europe being associated with cool  biotopes. In the UK moorlands and atlantic. Additional NT criteria Threats main forage plant (angelica) highly palatable threatened by agricultural intensification and threats also agricultural abandonment with scrub succession and woodland creation/tree planting a threat in west cornwall. (Requiring specialised habitats of marginal agricultural value) Threat UK continued decline of food plant https://plantatlas2020.org/atlas/2cd4p9h.8axEuropean threat level high.  B1 & B2 = VU  ?","1","disagree"
"Andrena russala: iso. Praz et al: 2022","212","LC ? NT ?","Paddy Saunders","","No Data file. Needs more scrutiny. Probable decline. Map could indicate decline.  Now extremely fragmented Cornwall only one site. Only 2 sites Exmoor 2 or so Dartmoor. Widely recorded in past Confusion/misidentification with A.wilkella probable in records and mask change. Southern England BWARS records post 2010 show possible decline ? Threats- climate risk Upland species in SW","1","Disagree ?"
"Andrena simillima: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT ","Paddy Saunders","","Research indicates populations in Cornwall (this research covering possibly over 50% of the range http://kernowecology.co.uk/Publications/3163.pdf ) are fragmented.  This indicates the species has limited dispersal from key sites, which are small areas with high quality pollen resources. putting threats including stochastic events and intensive agriculture/land management. The two main population clusters west Cornwall and Salisbury plain are widely separated. AOO/EOO may overestimate distribution as proportion of grid squares sea. Threats- climate risk the (english sub.) species has an Atlantic distribution in Europe being associated with a cool maritime biotope.  Threats-unimproved grassland habitats still have habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices. Has a Conservation dependence as usually associated with specialized coastal habitats and cessation of conservation programme likely to result in higher threat level in short term. Threats- coastal development. Additional The British population may need higher Europe threat status pending species split of Andrena simillima group in taxonomic review (ref). B1 & B2 = VU","1","disagree"
"Andrena tarsata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Evidence decline in SW. Populations fragmented Dartmoor and Exmoor (only one site) some fragmentation and loss of sites Bodmin moor, poor population on Lizard. Possibly gone from mid Cornwall. REF Saunders 23. Although good population still on many sites. Climate risk- monitoring link between hot and dry summers and poor population size. REF Saunders 23. Threat- rotational bare ground creation many be important and limiting factor REF Saunders 23.","0","Y"
"Bombus bohemicus: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Paddy Saunders","","agree climate risk, don't have full stat knowledge to argue if VU/NT right status. But do see this species less frequently.","0","Y"
"Bombus campestris: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Paddy Saunders","","agree climate risk, don't have full stat knowledge to argue if VU/NT right status. Comment may shows general trends in habitat deterioration as a result of agricultural intensification The comment says ""host is increasing"", where is this evidence ??? a spread northward of b.pascorum may not result increased abundance or density of host. Beewalk data needed. Long-term trends interacting between Host and Clepto-parasites and landscape availability in resources are likely to be outside the ICUN time line. Probable Threat to host- Agricultural intensification and pernicious changes in wider farmland.","0","Y"
"Bombus humilis: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Still largely a coastal bee and maybe severely fragmented in Devon. Iconic and easy to identify, popular trends in recording bees likely to mask declines. Threats-unimproved grassland habitats still have habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices. Conservation dependence (both protected sites and subsidies) and cessation of conservation programme likely to result in higher threat level in short term. On the South Coast of the SW scrub succession is an increasing threat.  Threats- excess nitrogen in the farmland landscape from agriculture and industry (ref Carvalheiro 2020). Bumblebees are wide dispersers, with large landscape requirement and large A00 likely to mask true viable populations. B2 close to VU cat. ","1","ADD COMM"
"Bombus monticola: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Extinct Cornwall, probably declining Dartmoor and Exmoor, Threat climate risk. Threats- conservation dependance on high quality moorland sites","0","Y"
"Bombus muscorum: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","NT ","Paddy Saunders","","High decline rate in SW England was widespread in Devon and Cornwall now probably only one site in Devon and difficult to find in Cornwall 2024. Still present in Somerset Levels, but in small numbers. Difficulties in identification likely to mask rarity (more likely to recorded as muscorum than not). Threat- climate risk as associated with cooler and wetter sites. Threats-unimproved grassland habitats still have habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices and long term nitrogen deposition. Has a Conservation dependence as usually associated with high quality habitats and cessation of conservation programme likely to result in higher threat level in short term.   Bumblebees are wide dispersers, with large landscape requirement and large A00 likely to mask true viable populations. B2 close to VU cat. EU RDB considers species VU","1","disagree"
"Bombus ruderarius: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Extinct Cornwall and Devon. Not only an edge species, associated with species rich grassland  and more diverse agricultural habitats. Threats-unimproved legume habitats continued habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices. ","0","Y"
"Bombus ruderatus: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Expanding in Somerset but not expanding in Devon. Expansion has relied on conservation dependence (agricultural subsidy of legume rich options) and cessation of conservation program could result threat in short term. Threats-unimproved legume habitats still having habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices. ","0","Y"
"Bombus soroeensis: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","NT  ","Paddy Saunders","","High decline rate in SW England was widespread in Devon and Cornwall now extinct not under-recorded, although challenging to identify. Bumblebees are wide dispersers, with large landscape requirement and large A00 may mask true viable populations. Threats-unimproved grassland and moorland still have habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices and nitrogen deposition. Threat High climate risk associated with cooler and wetter sites. Evidence of UK decline in one important food plant https://plantatlas2020.org/atlas/2cd4p9h.23w B2 at VU cat ?","1","disagree"
"Bombus sylvarum: iso. Cameron et al: 2007","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Somerset Levels potentially extreme fragmentation, only present 2 or three sites in extensive survey 2019 Ref Saunders 19 Threats-Peat Workings convertion to reedbed (Ongoing negative impact) Threats climate risks- increased flooding (Most of former distribution occurs on wet meadows close to sea level)","0","Y"
"Eucera longicornis: iso. Amiet et al: 2007","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Still largely a coastal bee in SW and many sites with very small and fragmented populations. Iconic and easy to identify, popular trends in recording bees likely to mask declines in this species. Threats-unimproved grassland habitats continuing habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices. Has a Conservation dependence as usually associated with specialized coastal habitats and cessation of conservation programme likely to result in higher threat level in short term. Specific Threats Cornwall - Ref Saunders 2019. Threats habitat deterioration. Ref Saunders 24 (Devon) On the South Coast of the SW scrub succession is an increasing long term threat. Threats climate risk  strongly associated with soft cliff sites and is threatened by Climate change and Extreme weather events both winter storm surges and increased winter rainfall. B2 = VU ? A00 < 2000km","1","ADD COMM"
"Nomada argentata: iso. Amiet et al: 2007","212","NT ","Paddy Saunders","","High rate of historical decline in SW, probably extinct in Devon and Cornwall possibly Somerset.  Evidence of UK decline in food plant https://plantatlas2020.org/atlas/2cd4p9h.23w. Threat highly conservation dependant as large areas of flowering scabious scarce and at risk of unsuitable management. Populations Very fragmented reliant on very high quality scabious rich sites which are very very fragmented. Likely to be higher risk than host needing large host population. ","1","disagree"
"Nomada armata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT ","Paddy Saunders",""," High rate of historical decline, extinctions in Devon and Cornwall. Likely to require higher quality and larger sites than host to maintain viability. Poor evidence N.armata will join up with any extensions to western/northern/eastern host populations as calcareous grassland is not very connected. Threats-unimproved grassland habitats continued habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices as a highly specialized species this threat is more critical. High Conservation dependence on specialised sites (both protected sites and subsidies) and cessation of conservation programme likely to result in higher threat level in short term.  AOO =EN ? DEOO= VU ","1","disagree"
"Nomada conjungens: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT / LC ??","Paddy Saunders","","Whilst one of the hosts may have evidence of expansion. Threats climate risk The Nomada is often associated with soft cliff sites and is threatened by Climate change and Extreme weather events both winter storm surges and increased winter rainfall. It is difficult to record and may be more widespread but precautionary principle is valid for ICUN.","1","Disagree ?"
"Nomada integra: iso. Notton & Norman: 2017","212","NT / LC ??","Paddy Saunders","","Probably should be assigned a category. More likely to be found in SW on Moorland sites and usually as singletons and very difficult to find. Threat-possibly climate risk Threat Threats-unimproved grassland habitats still have habitat deterioration by changing agricultural practices","1","disagree"
"Nomada obtusifrons: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT ","Paddy Saunders","","Evidence of high decline in SW (e.g. only found on one site in Cornwall 2 ? in Devon). Threat Evidence of Host decline. Threat Climate threat.  More research needed on ecology of host and population ecology. b1/b2 aoo = EN eoo =VU. European threat.   ","1","disagree"
"Nomada roberjeotiana: iso. Amiet et al: 2007","212","NT ","Paddy Saunders","","The species has had targetted surveys and is no more likely to be under-recorded than many of common Nomada (Is easier to identify than most of lassioglossum species ). Does not warrant DD ICUN criteria suggests DD should be a last resort. fragmented population much more fragmented than host species, relying on pockets of high quality sites within larger landscape area of host. Bodmin Moor/Lizard isolated small . REF SAUNDERS. Threats- Probable historical decline of host in SW Exmoor and Dartmoor. Threats- climate risks Evidence of host decline in southern England probably due to Climate risks (England).  Threat- key sites with suitable stands of food plant still threatened by unsuitable management. Threats- extreme fluctuations in population size REF Saunders 24 European Threat - EU  RDB  b1/b2 aoo = EN eoo =VU ","1","disagree"
"Nomada sexfasciata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Paddy Saunders","","Potentially EX not found in extensive surveys in 2023/24. Ref Saunders 24. The host is NOT expanding in South Devon. There has been greatly improved survey effort and great public interest in a iconic and easily identifiable host bee. Threats South Devon has long term deterioration in habitat availability and quality due to agricultural abandonment of difficult slopes. Threats Climate change and Extreme weather events both winter storm surges and increased rainfall as nests occur in soft cliff. Threats Nomada may have extreme fluctuation in population size and may require a very strong host population. ","0","Y"
