"Andrena coitana: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Liam Olds","","Probably under-recorded in parts of the north and west, but I get the impression that it is doing well here (I frequently encounter it in Wales). A serious decline across large parts of it range however, especially southern and central England, which warrants NT. ","0","Y"
"Andrena confinis: iso. Wood: 2022","212","NT","Liam Olds","","Map suggests that it has declined in southern England and has a restricted UK distribution. Some of the known sites in South Wales that I am familiar with are brownfield sites that are threatened by natural succession, development, etc. As such, there is a realistic chance that populations could be lost here in the near future.  ","1","N"
"Andrena denticulata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Liam Olds","","","0","Y"
"Andrena dorsata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Liam Olds","","","0","Y"
"Andrena falsifica: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT","Liam Olds","","Map suggests that it has declined across southern England and has a restricted UK distribution. It has been recorded at number of new sites in South and Mid Wales in recent years and I suspect it is widespread and under-recorded here, albiet it does seem genuinely scarce (much scarcer than A. coitana and A. tarsata in the same habitats). It shows a reliance, however, on brownfield sites in South Wales which are threatened by natural succession, development, ect. As such, there is a realistic chance that populations could be lost here in the near future.  ","1","N"
"Andrena ferox: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT","Liam Olds","","Though I'm not personally familiar with this species, the map suggests a decline and a restricted distribution so perhaps it should be NT?","1","N"
