"Andrena niveata: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","VU","Liam Olds","","VU seems more appropriate since the species has a rather widespread distribution, is likely under-recorded in many areas, and the map appears to suggest that it hasn't declined as significantly as some other species with a lower threat status than EN. ","1","N"
"Andrena pilipes: iso. Else & Edwards: 2018","212","","Liam Olds","","","0","Y"
"Andrena polita: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","?","Liam Olds","","I assume it is NA because the narrative suggests it’s a ""recent re-colonist"". While it is certainly possible that this is the case, what proof is there to support this hypothesis? If it can't be proved to be a re-colonist, shouldn't it be assessed as a long-term resident? ","1","N"
"Andrena praecox: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Liam Olds","","","0","Y"
"Andrena proxima: iso. Falk et al: 2019","212","LC?","Liam Olds","","As per A. ampla comment, is there enough information in Falk et. al. 2019 to asign a Status? Based on examined specimens in that paper, proxima appears to be widespread in south-east England. Suspect its LC. ","1","N"
"Andrena rosae: iso. Else & Edwards: 2018","212","NT","Liam Olds","","It has a very restricted distribution and though records don't suggest a recent decline (perhaps due to targeted survey effort?), some of its associated habitats are vulnerable (e.g. to coastal development).  NT seems more appropriate.","1","N"
"Andrena ruficrus: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Liam Olds","","","0","Y"
"Andrena russala: iso. Praz et al: 2022","212","NT","Liam Olds","","Though it has a widespread distribution and is no doubt under-recorded in some areas, the map suggests it has declined over a large part of its range and NT seems more appropritate. At least in South Wales, it has an association with brownfield sites that are threatened by natural succession, reclamation schemes, etc., so it could be lost from some known sites in the region in the near future - I'm not sure if this is the case in other parts of its range? ","1","N"
"Andrena semilaevis: iso. Amiet et al: 2010","212","","Liam Olds","","","0","Y"
"Andrena simillima: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","NT?","Liam Olds","","It has a very restricted distribution that makes it vulnerable. Some of its associated habitats may also be vulnerable - e.g. coastal grasslands to agricultural intensification. NT or VU seems more appropriate. ","1","N"
"Andrena subopaca: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Liam Olds","","","0","Y"
"Andrena synadelpha: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","","Liam Olds","","","0","Y"
"Andrena tarsata: iso. Perkins: 1919","212","LC?","Liam Olds","","While it has declined in some parts of southern England, it seems to be doing okay in SW England, Wales, Scotland and parts of N England and its associated habitats are certainly not uncommon . Considering it is probably under-recorded in the north and west also, I don't think NT is warranted - perhaps LC is more appropriate?","1","N"
