"Coelioxys inermis: iso. Amiet et al: 2004","212","","Liam Olds","","","0","Y"
"Coelioxys mandibularis: iso. Amiet et al: 2004","212","NT","Liam Olds","","While it has a restricted national distribution, it appears to be doing well on the majority of its Welsh sites which account for a significant proportion of known hectards in UK. I have found this bee to be rather abundant on Welsh sand dunes (such as Merthyr Mawr, Kenfig, Pembrey Burrows) in summer (I find it to actually be among the most common solitary bees in these habitats in summer, and certainly much more abundant than other species you may expect in that habitat such as C. coinodea) and  widespread across these sites also. In recent years, projects such as the Sands for LIFE and others have been increasing the proportion of open sand on the major sand dunes across Wales and I have monitored the dune 'scrapes' at a few sites (Kenfig and Pembrey Burrows) are have found C. mandibularis to readily utilise them (following their host) and be present within just a a few years. As such, it is expected that an increase in suitable habitat (for host nesting) has occured across much of its Welsh sites in recent years. Combined with the discovery of additional new sites in recent years (e.g. a sandy brownfield land in Port Talbot in 2024 and on sand dune at Pyle & Kenfig Golf Course in 2021) and that the majoritity of its known sites are protected, I don't feel EN is an appropriate status and NT seems a better fit (or VU if the status can only go down by one cateogry).  I also believe it still present on Wirral as I've seen photo's of small Coelioxys females around M. leachella that I'm pretty sure are C. mandibularis but these observations are unconfirmed at present. ","1","N"
"Coelioxys quadridentata: iso. Amiet et al: 2004","212","","Liam Olds","","Seems genuinly rare and perhaps enough evidence of declines to warrant a threat status? ","1","N"
